comments.message:
> the NMI button is user-facing, so it seems useful to know if users are messing with buttons regardless of the state of the host.

I mean it's an event that the BMC can detect and log, but if the host isn't powered on to respond to an NMI in any way, I guess I'm sort of unclear on what's interesting or useful about it -- in that state it just seems kinda like a dummy GPIO.  I suppose it's conceivable that there could be situations in which it could be useful for some sort of post-mortem debugging or something?

The main problem we have is that on the hardware we've got that produces these spurious button-press events when the host shuts off, the logged events manifest as `CRITICAL`-level errors in the redfish event log, so in the web UI it looks like there's something deeply wrong with the system even when the only thing that's happened is a totally healthy shutdown.

> If hardware-specific patching isn't an option, perhaps this filter could be added as a build or configuration option?

A hardware-specific patch is what we're currently using internally, but we'd of course prefer to get something upstream instead, and patches in upstream OpenBMC have (quite reasonably, IMO) been disallowed for a while now.  I think it would be preferable to avoid increasing the number of compile-time options; perhaps we could add a config sub-section looking something like this?  (Arranged so as to be extensible to other event-logging customization.)

```
{
  "gpio_configs": [
    ...
  ],
  "timing_configs": {
    ...
  },
  "logging": {
    "LogNMIButtonPressWhenPoweredOff": false
  }
}
```

The name is a bit verbose, but I couldn't think of anything more concise that was still reasonably self-explanatory.  (Open to suggestions for better alternatives if anyone has any.)

I thought we wanted to block all NMI actions based on the host state?

This could be changed (if I got the logic right) to
```
        if (!nmiWhenPoweredOff &&
            getHostState(powerState) !=
                "xyz.openbmc_project.State.Host.HostState.Running")
        {
            return;
        }
```
